The force between two permanent magnets can be attractive or repulsive.
Two poles that are the same (these are called ‘like poles’) will repel each
other. Two different poles (‘unlike poles’) will attract each other.
The force between a permanent and an induced magnet is always attractive.
The magnetic eld is strongest at the poles of a magnet. So eld lines for
magnets are closest together at the poles, as shown in Figure 1. The further
away from a magnet you get, the weaker the eld is.
Uniform magnetic elds are created between two opposite magnetic poles.
Uniform elds have the same strength everywhere — so the eld lines are
evenly spaced, parallel, straight lines (see Figure 2).
